Constructing a Sample Network for Outlier Detection

Find the soft threshold for the sample network

powers=c(c(1:10),seq(from=12,to=20,by=2))
# choose power based on SFT criterion
sft=pickSoftThreshold(as.matrix(t(datExpr),powerVector=powers))
# Plot the results:
par(mfrow=c(1,2))
# SFT index as a function of different powers
plot(sft$fitIndices[,1],
-sign(sft$fitIndices[,3])*sft$fitIndices[,2],
xlab="Soft Threshold (power)",ylab="Scale Free Topology
Model Fit,
signed R2",type="n",main=paste("Scale independence"))
text(sft$fitIndices[,1],
-sign(sft$fitIndices[,3])*sft$fitIndices[,2],
labels=powers,col="red")
# this line corresponds to using an R2 cut-off of h
abline(h=0.90,col="red")
# Mean connectivity as a function of different powers
plot(sft$fitIndices[,1],sft$fitIndices[,5],type="n",
xlab="Soft Threshold (power)",ylab="Mean Connectivity",
main=paste("Mean connectivity"))
text(sft$fitIndices[,1],sft$fitIndices[,5],labels=powers,
col="red")

library(igraph)
graph_list = NULL
for (i in c(1:length(list_color_modules))){
  tmp = which(moduleColorsManual== list_color_modules[i])
  adj_mat = A[tmp,tmp]
  diag(adj_mat) <- 0
  rownames(adj_mat) <- colnames(datExpr_filtered)[tmp]
  colnames(adj_mat) <- colnames(datExpr_filtered)[tmp]
  graph_tmp <- graph_from_adjacency_matrix(adjmatrix = adj_mat, mode = "undirected",weighted = TRUE)
  graph_list[[i]] <- graph_tmp
}

Find the hub gene for each module by using igraph function

  • Hub gene was calcuated by igraph[3] package by using Kleinbergs hub centrality scores for weighted network by bicor weighted correlation by wgcna package
hub_s <- hub_score(graph_list[[1]])
hub_corlor <- rep("blue",length(hub_s$vector))
hub_corlor[which(hub_s$vector == max(hub_s$vector))] <- "red"
hub_size <- rep(3,length(hub_s$vector))
hub_size[which(hub_s$vector == max(hub_s$vector))] <- 6
hub_name <- rep(NA,length(hub_s$vector))
hub_name[which(hub_s$vector == max(hub_s$vector))] <- names(hub_s$vector)[which(hub_s$vector == max(hub_s$vector))]

library(igraph)
find_pos_list <- function(ver_names, list_names){
  ver = NULL

gradient_legend <- function(colors, values, title) {
  par(mar = c(0, 3, 2, 0))
  image(1, 1:length(colors), t(as.matrix(1:length(colors))),
        col = colors, axes = FALSE, xlab = "", ylab ="",xlim = c(1,1.2))
  axis(2, at = 1:length(colors), labels = values, las = 1)
  title(main = title, line = 0.2)
}

The following codes are for doing comparision between chosen groups. We can check if there are preserved modules (gene clusters) between 2 different groups, the differences of modules between them, etc.

First we need to choose the groups we want to separate the data into groups

Function to separate the data by chosen variable, design_traits has row names as library or samples

groups_sep <- function(var_name, data, design_traits){
  
  # Make sure the order of samples are the same between data and trait design matrix
  
  design_traits = design_traits[rownames(data),]
  
  # Get all the possible values from the category
  
  list_data <- list()
  
  list_cat <- unique(design_traits[,var_name])
  i <- 1
  for (e in list_cat){
    list_data[[i]] = data[which(design_traits[,var_name] == e),]
    i = i+1
  }
  names(list_data) <- list_cat
  return(c(list_data,design_traits))
}
